{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:24:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:24:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14146"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14146"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.11,0.59,0.11,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105599"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6829"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88027"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1228"},{"type":"tags","id":"3151"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45744"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105599"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about difficulty concentrating at work and disorganisation in her daily life. After a comprehensive assessment, she is diagnosed with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD). She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. You are considering prescribing stimulant medication as part of her treatment plan.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be performed prior to commencing stimulant medication in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid function tests and full blood count","Urine drug screen and serum electrolytes","Blood pressure measurement and heart rate assessment","Liver function tests and renal function tests","Fasting glucose and iron studies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen initiating stimulant medication for ADHD in adults, it is crucial to perform appropriate investigations to ensure patient safety. The most important initial investigations in this scenario are an \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood pressure measurement and heart rate assessment\u003C/strong\u003E. This combination provides a comprehensive evaluation of cardiovascular status, which is essential because stimulant medications can have cardiovascular effects, including increased heart rate and blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting glucose and iron studies\u003C/strong\u003E are not routinely required before starting stimulant medication unless there are specific clinical indications. While these tests can provide general information about a patient\u0027s health status, they are not specifically targeted at the risks associated with stimulant use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver function tests and renal function tests \u003C/strong\u003Eare not routinely recommended before starting stimulant medication. However, they may be considered if there is a history of liver or kidney disease, or if the patient is taking other medications that could affect these organ systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid function tests and full blood count \u003C/strong\u003Eare not typically necessary before initiating stimulant therapy for ADHD. While thyroid dysfunction can sometimes mimic ADHD symptoms, the diagnosis of ADHD should be based on a comprehensive clinical assessment rather than thyroid function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine drug screen and serum electrolytes \u003C/strong\u003Eare not routinely required before starting stimulant medication. However, a urine drug screen may be considered if there is a clinical suspicion of substance use disorder, as this could complicate ADHD treatment. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the blood pressure, and heart rate assessment, a thorough medical history and physical examination should be performed, with particular attention to cardiovascular risk factors. Some clinicians may also consider additional investigations based on individual patient factors and clinical judgment, but the cardiovascular assessment remains the most crucial initial investigation in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf note, for patients with pre-existing cardiac disease an ECG would also be required to identify any cardiac abnormalities that might increase the risk of adverse effects from stimulant medication. In this patient population it is particularly important to rule out conditions such as long QT syndrome or structural heart abnormalities that could be exacerbated by stimulants.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Baseline cardiovascular assessment, including blood pressure and heart rate, is essential before starting stimulant medication for ADHD in adults.","A comprehensive medical history and physical examination are crucial to identify any contraindications to stimulant therapy for ADHD in adults.","Routine blood tests are not mandatory but may be considered based on individual patient factors and clinical judgment prior to starting stimulant medication in ADHD."],"references":["May T, Birch E, Chaves K, Cranswick N, Culnane E, Delaney J, et al. The Australian evidence-based clinical practice guideline for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. Australian \u0026 New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry. 2023 Aug;57(8):1101-16. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37254562/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88027"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14146"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88027"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-10T21:35:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T21:35:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6829"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105599"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"a